A [land use management system](/Land_use_planning) dedicated to the cultivation, protection, and overall well-being of [trees](/Tree) and [shrubs](/Shrub) within developed areas.

For those seeking to understand the mere *presence* of [forests](/Forest) within municipal boundaries, consult the [Urban forest](/Urban_forest) article. This, however, delves into the deliberate, often Sisyphean, task of managing them.

### Urban forestry in [New York City](/New_York_City)

[Urban forestry](/Urban_forestry) isn't just about letting a few [trees](/Tree) exist; it's the meticulous, often thankless, process of caring for and strategically managing individual arboreal specimens and entire arboreal [populations](/Population) within the intricate labyrinth of [urban](/Urban_area) landscapes. The overarching, arguably optimistic, goal is to enhance the very fabric of the [urban environment](/Urban_environment). Sometimes quaintly referred to as the [urban tree canopy](/Canopy_(biology)), this discipline demands both foresight in [planning](/Urban_planning) and diligent execution in ongoing [management](/Forest_management), encompassing everything from initial planting schemes to the perpetual cycle of care and maintenance operations that keep the [urban forest](/Urban_forest) from collapsing into arboreal chaos.

Proponents of [urban forestry](/Urban_forestry) aren't merely tree-huggers; they assert, with compelling evidence, that [trees](/Tree) are an indispensable, indeed critical, component of modern [urban infrastructure](/Urban_infrastructure). The professionals who navigate this complex field—[urban foresters](/Forester), alongside municipal and commercial [arborists](/Arborists), utility foresters, [environmental policymakers](/Environmental_policy), astute [city planners](/City_planner), various consultants, dedicated educators, diligent researchers, and even the occasional impassioned [community activist](/Community_organizing)—are tasked with the planting, rigorous maintenance, and steadfast preservation of suitable [trees](/Tree) and [forest](/Forest) fragments. Their collective efforts are not just about aesthetics; they actively conduct [research](/Research) and tirelessly promote the myriad benefits these green sentinels bestow upon our concrete jungles. A prime example of their practical impact is the proven ability of [urban forests](/Urban_forest) to significantly mitigate the oppressive effects of the [urban heat island](/Urban_heat_island) phenomenon, achieving this through the natural processes of [evapotranspiration](/Evapotranspiration) and the strategic shading of sun-baked streets and imposing buildings.

Unfortunately, this ideal vision often collides with a stark reality: the profound [environmental impacts](/Environmental_impact) stemming from the stark inequity in [urban tree canopy](/Canopy_(biology)) distribution. Yet, in a world grappling with impending ecological collapse, the strategic act of [planting trees](/Tree_planting) stands as a remarkably effective, thoroughly proven method for both [climate change adaptation](/Climate_change_adaptation) and its ongoing [mitigation](/Climate_change_mitigation). Beyond human concerns, these [urban forests](/Urban_forest) also serve as crucial havens for [wildlife](/Urban_wildlife), attracting various species due to the enhanced availability of surface waters—a direct consequence of reduced [stormwater runoff](/Surface_runoff) in these vegetated zones. For the human inhabitants, the integration of [forests](/Forest) into [urban environments](/Urban_environment) has demonstrated tangible, beneficial effects, ranging from promoting psychological healing and facilitating stress recovery to significantly improving concentration and overall [productivity](/Productivity). Even humble [street trees](/Street_tree), when meticulously managed and consistently cared for, contribute immensely to the creation of truly [sustainable](/Sustainability) and healthy communities. However, this rosy picture is consistently marred by the inequitable distribution of this vital canopy cover, particularly in neighborhoods of lower [socioeconomic status](/Socioeconomic_status), a disparity that invariably gives rise to serious [environmental justice](/Environmental_justice) issues.

## Benefits

### Environmental and health impacts

#### Tree canopy over [Midtown Sacramento](/Midtown_Sacramento) suburban street

The sheer lethality of [heat waves](/Heat_wave) is often underestimated, claiming approximately 1,300 lives annually within the [United States](/United_States) alone. This grim statistic surpasses the mortality rate of any other weather-related event, a number we can only expect to escalate as global temperatures continue their relentless ascent. The vulnerability is particularly acute for low-income households, often lacking access to crucial [air conditioning](/Air_conditioning), and for inherently heat-sensitive demographics such as the elderly, infants, and individuals burdened by chronic health conditions.

The simple, yet profound, act of [reforesting](/Reforestation) an area demonstrably mitigates this heat burden. A 10-meter radius of new forest cover can induce a 0.7 degree Celsius reduction in daytime air temperature. Expand that to a 30-meter radius, and the decrease nearly doubles to 1.3 degrees Celsius. For those truly committed to cooling, a 60 or 90-meter radius yields a remarkable reduction exceeding 1.5 degrees. This isn't just a trivial comfort; it directly translates into a reduced risk of debilitating [heat stroke](/Heat_stroke), tangible decreases in exorbitant cooling costs, and a general, albeit often unappreciated, improvement in overall human well-being.

